    {
      "id": "e92b45af6dd8600d8375fce6e13660260a9e4a49",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-01-18 03:56:52.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\n(3 comments)\n\nThanks for reviving this work. It would be great to have a lustre test for this, but I don't think we configure redundant devices for ZFS in our normal test config. It might be possible to set up a mirrored/raidz OST in conf-sanity with loop devices?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e7fbe13df60f04cee5736d00340a61127a837fb2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-01-18 04:06:33.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nHmm, one other option is to just call the zedlet directly with the expected args to verify that it is working (via \"lctl get_param\") then verify the MDS is skipping that OST at least by some fraction. It looks like there is already a degraded OST test we can leverage - sanity 27x. It is worthwhile to verify this is also working with PFL files. \n\nOne problem I recall with degraded OSTs is that the index after the degraded OST would get 2x the number of objects as others. It is worthwhile to check that this has been fixed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
